          <div class="cmsmasters_text">
            <h2 class="cmsmasters_heading">Dental Appliance vs CPAP</h2>
            <p>While CPAP may be the most common sleep apnea treatment option around, it is also likely the least tolerated. If you’re one of those currently on CPAP therapy and find difficulty coping with it, you’re not alone.</p>
            <p>CPAP can be highly beneficial if patients use them properly. The problem is, the majority of patients struggle to comply with CPAP directives. The therapy requires patients to wear a nasal mask, ideally throughout the night, to allow an influx of pressurised air to keep their throats from collapsing during sleep. Approx 60% of patients stay with their nightly cpap therapy to obtain the desired results. Some CPAP users only manage to keep the mask on for 4 hours or less per night. Some users experience one or more of the following compliance issues: Nasal irritation, dry mouth, sore throat, acne breakouts (due to the straps), runny nose, allergies, etc.</p><p>If you happen to be one of those patients experiencing CPAP compliance issues, you would be happy to know that ex-CPAP users have successfully transitioned over to oral appliance therapy. Some patients have both! CPAP for home, and MAS for travel and camping. If you’re interested, speak to our sleep physician about the possibility of switching to a dental appliance.</p>
           </div>
           </div>
        </div>
        </div>
       </div>
                  
